ng of variable elements, including language, literary devices, plot, and characters. The contributions in this volume establish that many texts written in the medieval and early modern Jewish communities across Europe and beyond can be classified as "romance.” Each of the nine chapters as well as the afterword by Eli Yassif discusses romance as it relates to the medieval and early modern Jewish world, as well as the greater non-Jewish context. This volume places Jewish texts into the scholarly conversation as sources for forming a new understanding of the genre of romance across religious and cultural boundaries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJewish literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aRomancesxHistory and criticism. 0aRomances, HebrewxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aHebrew Arthurian romance.  aMedieval vernacular literature.  apremodern Jewish culture.1 aBernuth, Ruth Von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBibring, Tovi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyarin, Shamma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFishbane, Eitan P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFishkin, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGruenbaum, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGruenbaum, Caroline, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKushelevsky, Rella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLembke, Astrid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOehme, Annegret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOehme, Annegret, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt